    "keyTakeaways": [
      "The biggest value drivers are make/model demand, mileage, age, and overall condition inside and out.",
      "Trim and options matter: AWD, leather, and tech/safety packages typically raise a vehicle's value over a base model.",
      "A clean accident and ownership history plus complete service records help protect resale value; gaps and damage tend to reduce it.",
      "In Alberta, season and local demand count — trucks and AWD vehicles tend to hold their value well through winter.",
      "Accurate offers weigh all of these factors against live wholesale market data, so honest, complete details produce the most accurate number."
    ],
    "faqs": [
      {
        "q": "How much does mileage actually affect my car's value?",
        "a": "Mileage is one of the strongest single factors because it signals remaining lifespan and upcoming maintenance. A vehicle with well-below-average kilometres for its age usually commands a premium, while high mileage tends to discount the price. There's no fixed per-kilometre rule, though, since condition, model demand, and service history can offset or amplify the effect."
      },
      {
        "q": "Does an accident-free history or a clean vehicle history report really raise my offer?",
        "a": "It generally helps. A documented accident-free history and complete service records reduce a buyer's risk, which can support a stronger price. Reported accidents, frame damage, or a branded title typically lower value even after quality repairs because they affect future resale. Having your records and a current history report ready up front helps your offer reflect the car's real condition."
      },
      {
        "q": "Why might my truck or AWD vehicle hold its value well in Alberta?",
        "a": "Local demand shapes value, and Alberta winters keep trucks, SUVs, and all-wheel-drive vehicles in steady demand. Strong regional demand generally means these vehicles tend to hold their value better than comparable two-wheel-drive cars, though the specific model and its condition still matter most. Season can also play a role, with some body styles peaking at different times of year."
      },
      {
        "q": "Do upgrades and aftermarket modifications increase my car's value?",
        "a": "Factory options like leather, AWD, and tech or safety packages usually add value because buyers recognize and want them. Aftermarket modifications are different — most don't return their cost, and some (lift kits, tunes, non-standard wheels) can narrow your buyer pool and lower value. An original, well-maintained factory configuration tends to appraise best."
      }
    ],
